REPORT:
- Create and download key pair from: https://us-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/v2/home?region=us-west-1#KeyPairs:sort=keyName
- SSH setup:
    + ssh-agent bash
    + ssh-add [LOCATION_TO_PEM_FILE]
- Generate three Elastic IPs from: https://us-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/v2/home?region=us-west-1#Addresses:sort=publicIp
- Create or modify a security group to allow all traffic(inbound and outbound) at: https://us-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/v2/home?region=us-west-1#SecurityGroups:sort=groupId
NOTE: write down the security group name
- Launch three EC2 ubuntu instances from: https://us-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/v2/home?region=us-west-1#Instances:sort=instanceId
NOTE: Use the same security group you previously modified. After launching one instance, can use 'launch more like this' to simplify
- Attach the previously created Elastic IPs to the EC2 instances
- Make the elastic IP entries in the 'hosts' file
- ssh-keygen -f "~/.ssh/known_hosts" -R [IP]
(If required, i.e., Key signature changes on every time an instance is destroyed and created )
- ssh-keyscan [host] >> ~/.ssh/known_hosts
(Add instance signatures to known hosts)
- use the script.sh to run the playbook
(NOTE: username on amazon linux VM is ec2-user, and on ubuntu VM is ubuntu)

GIT https://github.ncsu.edu/uskomarl/hpcc5.git

REFERENCE:https://github.com/a-h/ansible-mongodb-cluster
